ik</i>, from Old Norse <i>Eiríkr</i> (see   Erickson  ). Compare   Erickson  ,   Ericsson  , and   Erikson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Erikson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Anders, Nils, Astrid, Berndt, Iver, Karsten, Lars, Lennart, Lief, Thor.  German Gerhart, Ernst.","Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish   Eriksson  . This is also an Americanized form of the Norwegian, Danish, and North German cognate   Eriksen  . Compare   Erekson   and   Erickson  ."]},{"name":"Erickson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Nels, Thor, Nils, Lars, Sven, Lief, Anders, Lennart, Iver, Elof, Erland.","Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish   Ericsson   and   Eriksson  , Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Eriksen   and   Erichsen  , or of any other Scandinavian or North German patronymic from a personal name derived from Old Norse <i>Eiríkr</i>, which is composed of <i>ei</i> ‘ever, always’ (or a shortened form of <i>ein</i> ‘one, only’) + <i>rík</i> ‘power’. Compare   Ericksen  ,   Ericson  , and   Erikson  .","English (Lancashire): patronymic from the Middle English male personal name <i>Eric</i> (with the same etymology as 1 above) + <i>son</i>."]},{"name":"Erekson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Thor.","Americanized form of Swedish   Eriksson   or of any other Scandinavian patronymic from a personal name derived from Old Norse <i>Eiríkr</i> (see   Erickson  )."]},{"name":"Ericsson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Lars, Sven, Anders, Britt, Gunvor, Johan, Kerstin, Tor.","Swedish: variant of   Eriksson  . Compare   Erickson   and   Ericson  ."]}]},{"name":"Knut","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Old Norse <i>Knútr</i> ‘knot’, originally a byname given to a short, squat man.  King Knut  (  d. 1035 ) ruled over Denmark, Norway, and England in the 11th century; he is known in English as Canute. His great-nephew Knut (  d. 1086 ) was another king of Denmark; he was murdered by opponents of the laws enforcing payment of tithes to the Church and was canonized as a martyr. His nephew, also Knut (  d. 1131 ), was Duke of Schleswig and is also venerated as a martyr, although for what reason is not clear."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Knut Eriksson was born after 1140, in Uppsala, Sweden, his father, Erik \"den Helige\" Jedvardsson, was 8843 and his mother, Kristina Björnsdotter, was 8878. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Cecilia Johansdotter. He died after 1195, in Eriksberg, Västra Götaland, Sweden, and was buried in Varnhem, Västra Götaland, Sweden."},"et":{"after 1140–after 1195":"pärast 1140–pärast 1195","1140–1195":"1140–1195","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1155–1209":"1155–1209","–1156":"–1156","1145–1193":"1145–1193","1180–1216":"1180–1216","–Female":"Surnud","1156–1160":"1156–1160","1122–1170":"1122–1170","about 1180":"umbes 1180","after 1193":"pärast 1193","1195":"1195","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","1122":"1122","1155":"1155","after 1140":"pärast 1140","after 1195":"pärast 1195","before 1170":"enne 1170","1209":"1209","18 May 1160":"18. mai 1160","Sweden":"Rootsi","Varnhem, Västra Götaland, Sweden":"Varnhem, Västra Götaland, Rootsi","Uppsala, Sweden":"Uppsala, Rootsi","Eriksberg, Västra Götaland, Sweden":"Eriksberg, Västra Götaland, Rootsi"},"fi":{"after 1140–after 1195":"1140 jälkeen–1195 jälkeen","1140–1195":"1140–1195","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1155–1209":"1155–1209","–1156":"–1156","1145–1193":"1145–1193","1180–1216":"1180–1216","–Female":"Kuollut","1156–1160":"1156–1160","1122–1170":"1122–1170","about 1180":"noin 1180","after 1193":"1193 jälkeen","1195":"1195","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","1122":"1122","1155":